Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Although cases of encephalitis in children in this area of Uttar Pradesh are not unusual, with Japanese encephalitis virus infections responsible for some, the above report does not indicate the etiological agent responsible for these 6 encephalitis cases. The ages of the encephalitis cases are not given so one cannot tell if they are among the 15 younger than one month. There is no etiology offered for any of these cases.

Previous reports indicate that JE is a minor cause of encephalitis in northeastern Uttar Pradesh and Bihar states. The determination of the etiology or etiologies of acute encephalitis syndrome (AES) has been confusing and elusive. AES has continued to be attributed to a variety of etiologies, including Reye syndrome-like disease, possible enterovirus infection from polluted water, heat stroke, scrub typhus (_Orientia tsutsugamushi_), and lychee fruit consumption. Recently, scrub typhus has been implicated in many AES cases but is very unlikely for infants less than one month of age.

Maps of India can be accessed at http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5426319,142. - Mod.TY]
